 exhibition at Kunstverein München that follows from three previous projects this year in New York, Athens, and Bregenz. Their titles combine to form a single looping sentence: I’ll be your interface Broadcasting from the Aether At 1:1 Scale On a Universal Serial Bus.* \r\n\r\n<u>On a Universal Serial Bus.*</u> is based on a simultaneous publication of Dexter Sinister’s audio/visual works released in the form of a Universal Serial Bus (USB) memory stick. This drive offers a collection of digital files, while the exhibition presents those same files as a series of objects and installations, along with some related material via the Kunstverein’s regular mediation and promotional channels. Each of the four rooms in the exhibition is based on one of the four projects on the USB stick.\r\n\r\nA speaking asterisk (*) will greet visitors at the entry staircase in place of the usual introductory wall text. Dexter Sinister have programmed this glyph to speak the memory stick’s explanatory readme.txt file in the synthesized voice of curator Isla Leaver-Yap.\r\n\r\nUpstairs, the Kopfsaal will house a three-screen video installation called <u>Identity</u>. This 20-minute projection offers a critical look at the branding strategies of museums, using case studies of Tate, MoMA, and Centre Pompidou, narrated by a voiceover collaged from existing texts. \r\n\r\nThe Treppensaal will accommodate True Mirror, Dexter Sinister’s sprawling project for the 2008 <u>Whitney Biennial</u>. Originally staged as a three-week parallel press office operated from a secret office hidden in the walls of the exhibition, this project extended into multiple formats, including a ‘documents opera’ staged in New York and London, where the original material was performed by its protagonists. The space includes an edited video of this event, a Double-AA side record containing two of the project’s constituent ‘press releases’, a condensed microfiche archive of the initial project, a 16-mm flicker film of the same, and a mirror that offers visitors a view of themselves as others see them.\r\n\r\nThe Grossersaal will host <u>The Last ShOt Clock</u>, a project originally commissioned for <u>Oo/oO</u>, the joint Lithuanian/Cypriot Pavillion at the 2013 <u>Venice Biennial</u>. The space is dominated by two electronic LED scoreboards that keep eccentric time (or score) in their own binary code, plus a musical theme that was part of an hour-long ‘incantation’ delivered live by Dexter Sinister in Vilnius on summer solstice, 2014. Also in the space are a reprogrammed Casio watch that scrolls time digital line segment by digital line segment, an advert for the same, a poster made from light that advertises any and all summer solstices, a photograph of the original Venice clocks in situ, and the tiny microchips that ran them.\r\n\r\nThe Kleinersaal will contain the final piece on the Bus, called <u>Letter & Spirit</u>. This concise animated video tracks the history of the rationalization of typefaces, and adds temporality to typography via a shapeshifting typeface <u>Meta-the-difference-between-the-two-font-4-D</u>. Nearby on the walls are a print of an emblematic glyph, and a poster that announces this particular screening of the work.\r\n\r\nFinally a publication, number 3 in the Kunstverein’s <u>Companion</u> series, will be available at the opening on 2 October 2015. It provides supplementary material written and formatted from within the middle of the production of each piece: the script for <u>Identity</u>, a poem that initiated <u>True Mirror</u>, the complete ‘incantation’ from <u>The Last ShOt Clock</u>, and the full-length essay version of <u>Letter & Spirit</u>. ',''),(1372,1,'2015-10-11 15:08:41','2015-11-12 11:30:51',NULL,'Student Art Collective, <u>The Lesson of the Master</u>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'student-art-collective-uthe-lesson-of-the-masteru',NULL,'2015-10-27 19:00:00','2015-10-27 21:00:00',NULL,NULL,'','Behind the Green Door\r\nMontag, 26. Oktober 2015\r\n19.00 Uhr\r\n\r\nDas Student Art Collective ist eine erzieherische Initiative, die eine andere Art der Ausbildung anstrebt: Statt bloßer Ablehnung der üblichen passiven, langweiligen ödipalen und cyber-merkantilen Modelle, die im Kunstunterricht praktiziert werden, fordert sie einen aktiven militanten Boykott.\r\n\r\nDie Künstlergruppe veröffentlicht Drucksachen, organisiert Workshops in Akademien in Europa und den USA und macht Ausstellungen.\r\n \r\n<u>The Lesson of the Master</u> ist ein Kurzdrama im Stil eines Sokratischen Dialogs, das sich mit den welchselseitigen Problemen zwischen Lehrende und Studierende im Kunstbereich befasst.\r\n\r\nOrganisiert vom Kurator des Kunstverein München Saim Dermican. Vergangene Veranstaltungen von ‚Behind the Green Door‘ involvierten die Künstler Stephan Dillemuth, Dan Mitchell, John Russell und Head Gallery. Die Serie geht nun mit dem Student Art Collective und Feminist Land Art Retreat weiter. \r\n\r\n<iframe src=\"https://player.vimeo.com/video/145041962\" width=\"500\" height=\"281\" frameborder=\"0\" webkitallowfullscreen mozallowfullscreen allowfullscreen></iframe>\r\n\r\n',''),(1374,1,'2015-10-18 13:21:26','2015-11-23 14:20:39',NULL,'Dexter Sinister',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'dexter-sinister',NULL,'2015-10-02 00:00:00','2015-10-02 00:00:00',NULL,NULL,'','Dexter Sinister\r\n<u>On a Universal Serial Bus*</u>\r\n\r\n<a href=\'http://www.orderromapublications.org/publications/on-a-universal-serial-bus-*/92601&page=\'>ORDER</a>\r\n\r\nMunich, 2015\r\nEnglish / German\r\n\r\nEdited by Dexter Sinister (Stuart Bailey and David Reinfurt), Chris Fitzpatrick, Julie Peeters.\r\n\r\nPublished by Kunstverein München and Roma Publications, distributed by Idea Books.\r\n\r\nDesigned by Julie Peeters\r\n\r\nPrinted by Benedict Press in an edition of 750.',''),(1375,1,'2015-10-20 19:42:09','2015-10-20 19:52:21',NULL,'.markdown test',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'markdown-test',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','Dexter Sinister\r\n*On a Universal Serial Bus.\\**\r\n2 October to 22 November 2015\r\n\r\n[Dexter Sinister](http://dextersinister.org/) is the compound name of Stuart Bailey and David Reinfurt. Dexter Sinister work at the intersection of graphic design, publishing, and art. _On a Universal Serial Bus.*_ is a survey exhibition at Kunstverein München that follows from three previous projects this year in New York, Athens, and Bregenz. Their titles combine to form a single looping sentence: I’ll be your interface Broadcasting from the Aether At 1:1 Scale On a Universal Serial Bus.* ',''),(1377,1,'2015-10-29 13:07:56','2015-12-04 16:20:09',NULL,'<u>Jahresgaben 2015</u>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'ujahresgaben-2015u',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','<u>Jahresgaben</u>\r\n5. bis 13. Dezember 2015</u>\r\nEröffnung: Freitag, 4. Dezember, 19 Uhr\r\ngeöffnet täglich 11-18 Uhr\r\n\r\nMit den Jahresgaben präsentiert der Kunstverein München jährlich ein attraktives Angebot zeitgenössischer Kunst im Rahmen einer Verkaufsausstellung. Gezeigt werden Arbeiten von Künstlerinnen und Künstlern, die in München und Umgebung leben und arbeiten.\r\n\r\nMit der Jahresgaben-Ausstellung bringt der Kunstverein seine Verbundenheit mit der Münchner Künstlerschaft zum Ausdruck. Durch den Kauf einer Jahresgabe wird nicht nur der Kunstverein und sein zukünftiges Programm unterstützt, sondern auch junge Künstlerinnen und Künstler in München. Von der jeweiligen Verkaufssumme gehen 50% an die Künstlerinnen und Künstler, 45% verbleiben als Provision beim Kunstverein, die übrigen 5% werden an die Künstlersozialkasse abgeführt.\r\n\r\nBedingung für den Kauf ist die Mitgliedschaft im Kunstverein München. Es ist möglich, auch erst beim Kauf einer Jahresgabe Mitglied zu werden.\r\n\r\nDas Jahresgaben PDF mit allen Arbeiten steht <a href=\'http://www.kunstverein-muenchen.de/MEDIA/03615.pdf\' target=\'_blank\'>hier</a> zum Download bereit.\r\n\r\n\r\nJahresgaben Künstler 2015 \r\n\r\nNiko Abramidis \r\nFabian Aigner\r\nBoban Andjelkovic \r\nMojé Assefjah\r\nAbel Auer\r\nFlorian Auer\r\nMaximiliane Baumgartner\r\nNigin Beck\r\nBenjamin Bergmann\r\nScarlet Berner\r\nDavid Blitz\r\nAyzit Bostan\r\nLena Bröcker\r\nFriederike Daumiller\r\nIsabelle Dyckerhoff\r\nHedwig Eberle\r\nStefan Eberstadt\r\nJudith Egger\r\nMartin Fengel\r\nFriederike & Uwe\r\nFlorian Gass\r\nUlrich Gebert\r\nSusi Gelb\r\nJon Groom\r\nMichael Grudziecki\r\nZita Habarta\r\nFlaka Haliti\r\nJohannes Haslinger\r\nElias Hassos\r\nHaubitz+Zoche\r\nRuth Höflich\r\nStefan Hunstein\r\nKaren Irmer\r\nStephan Janitzky\r\nCaro Jost\r\nKAYA (Kerstin Brätsch und Debo Eilers)\r\nJosef Knoll\r\nAylin Langreuter\r\nJustin Lieberman\r\nNina Annabelle Märkl\r\nAnna McCarthy\r\nMichaela Melián\r\nVincent Mitzev\r\nChristian Muscheid\r\nAndreas Neumeister\r\nOlaf Nicolai\r\nCarsten Nolte\r\nJonas von Ostrowski \r\nPfaller & Kipphardt\r\nChristina Maria Pfeifer\r\nHeike Pillemann\r\nThomas von Poschinger \r\nOlaf Probst\r\nSybille Rath\r\nBerthold Reiß\r\nMirja Reuter\r\nPeter Sauerer\r\nLisa Schairer\r\nHank Schmidt in der Beek\r\nMax Schmidtlein\r\nRichard Schur\r\nFiona Struengmann\r\nFlorian Süssmayr\r\nVeronika Veit\r\nJulien Viala\r\nNina Walser\r\nJess Walter\r\nStefan Wischnewski\r\nMartin Wöhrl\r\nYoujin Yi',''),(1376,1,'2015-10-29 13:06:12','2015-12-04 16:21:20',NULL,'<u>Jahresgaben 2015</u>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'ujahresgaben-2015u',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','*Jahresgaben*\r\n5 to 13 December 2015\r\n\r\nWith the 2015 *Jahresgaben* exhibition, Kunstverein München presents a diverse selection of work by 70 contemporary artists who live and work in Munich and the surrounding area. The exhibition is open to the public, but the works can be purchased at special prices exclusively by members of Kunstverein München.\r\n\r\nThe *Jahresgaben* exhibition continues Kunstverein München\'s connection to the local contemporary art scene and sales support both the Kunstverein and artists. 50% of each sale supports the artist, 45% supports the Kunstverein, and the remaining 5% goes towards social insurance for artists.\r\n\r\nBeing a member of Kunstverein München is a requirement to purchase a work, though it is easy to become a member when making a purchase.\r\n\r\nA PDF with all the Jahresgaben is available for download <a href=\'http://www.kunstverein-muenchen.de/MEDIA/03615.pdf\' target=\'_blank\'>here</a>.\r\n\r\nNiko Abramidis \r\nFabian Aigner\r\nBoban Andjelkovic \r\nMojé Assefjah\r\nAbel Auer\r\nFlorian Auer\r\nMaximiliane Baumgartner\r\nNigin Beck\r\nBenjamin Bergmann\r\nScarlet Berner\r\nDavid Blitz\r\nAyzit Bostan\r\nLena Bröcker\r\nFriederike Daumiller\r\nIsabelle Dyckerhoff\r\nHedwig Eberle\r\nStefan Eberstadt\r\nJudith Egger\r\nMartin Fengel\r\nFriederike & Uwe\r\nFlorian Gass\r\nUlrich Gebert\r\nSusi Gelb\r\nJon Groom\r\nMichael Grudziecki\r\nZita Habarta\r\nFlaka Haliti\r\nJohannes Haslinger\r\nElias Hassos\r\nHaubitz+Zoche\r\nRuth Höflich\r\nStefan Hunstein\r\nKaren Irmer\r\nStephan Janitzky\r\nCaro Jost\r\nKAYA (Kerstin Brätsch and Debo Eilers)\r\nJosef Knoll\r\nAylin Langreuter\r\nJustin Lieberman\r\nNina Annabelle Märkl\r\nAnna McCarthy\r\nMichaela Melián\r\nVincent Mitzev\r\nChristian Muscheid\r\nAndreas Neumeister\r\nOlaf Nicolai\r\nCarsten Nolte\r\nJonas von Ostrowski \r\nPfaller & Kipphardt\r\nChristina Maria Pfeifer\r\nHeike Pillemann\r\nThomas von Poschinger \r\nOlaf Probst\r\nSybille Rath\r\nBerthold Reiß\r\nMirja Reuter\r\nPeter Sauerer\r\nLisa Schairer\r\nHank Schmidt in der Beek\r\nMax Schmidtlein\r\nRichard Schur\r\nFiona Struengmann\r\nFlorian Süssmayr\r\nVeronika Veit\r\nJulien Viala\r\nNina Walser\r\nJess Walter\r\nStefan Wischnewski\r\nMartin Wöhrl\r\nYoujin Yi',''),(1378,1,'2015-10-30 15:58:44','2015-12-03 17:52:34',9,'Dexter Sinister',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'dexter-sinister',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','Dexter Sinister\r\nDot Dot Dot poster, 2005/2015\r\nSiebdruck auf Poster und Karton\r\n80 x 59,4 cm\r\nAuflage: 10 + 6 AP\r\nsigniert und nummeriert \r\n\r\nEUR 250,00\r\n\r\nDas Poster wurde 2005 in Tallin, Estland, gedruckt, um für eine Ausstellung zu werben, in der Material aus der Kunstzeitschrift Dot Dot Dot gezeigt wurde. Auf die leere Fläche oben wurden jeweils die Ausstellungsdaten gedruckt. Demselben Zweck diente anders­wo der Restbestand der Auflage, da es sich um eine Wanderausstellung handelte, die an verschiedenen Orten gezeigt wurde. Irgend­wann jedoch waren die Poster plötzlich verschwunden – und blieben es, bis sie zehn Jahre später im Speicher des Kunstvereins München gefunden wurden. Anlässlich der Ausstellung <u>On a Universal Serial Bus.*</u> von Dexter Sinister, den ehemaligen Heraus­gebern der Kunstzeitschrift, sind die letzten zehn Poster nun als Edition erhältlich.',''),(1379,1,'2015-10-30 16:01:03','2015-11-25 14:20:55',NULL,'Dexter Sinister',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'dexter-sinister',NULL,'2015-10-03 00:00:00','2015-10-03 00:00:00',NULL,NULL,'','Dexter Sinister\r\nDot Dot Dot poster, 2005/2015\r\nScreenprint on poster and card\r\n80 x 59.4 cm\r\nEdition of 10 (+ 6 AP’s), signed and numbered by the artists\r\n\r\nThis poster was printed in 2005 in Tallin, Estonia, to advertise an exhibition of source material drawn from the arts journal Dot Dot Dot. The open space at the top was overprinted with the show’s exhibition dates, and the remainder of the print run intended to serve the same purpose else-where as the show moved on from place to place. However, somewhere along the way, the posters were misplaced – and remained so until found ten years later in the attic of Kunstverein München. The last ten are now put to latent use as an edition made available on the occasion of an exhibition by the journal’s former publishers Dexter Sinister called <u>On a Universal Serial Bus.*</u>',''),(1380,1,'2015-10-30 16:10:34','2015-10-30 20:55:37',3,'Stellenausschreibungen',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'stellenausschreibungen',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<a href=\'Koordinator@kunstverein-muenchen.de\'>Vertikal Klub</a>\r\n','<u>Koordinator (m/w): Fundraising, Pressearbeit und kuratorische Assistenz</u>\r\n \r\nDer 1823 gegründete Kunstverein München veranstaltet ein ambitioniertes Programm, das Ausstellungen zeitgenössischer Kunst, Events, Publikationen und Screenings umfasst. 2016 wird der Kunstverein seine Aktivitäten mit einem neuen Kino und einem Buchladen weiter ausbauen und sucht zur Unterstützung des Teams für die Mitarbeit bei der Organisation des künstlerischen Programms einen neuen Koordinator (m/w).\r\n \r\nDer Aufgabenbereich des Koordinators (m/w) umfasst vorrangig die folgenden Bereiche:\r\n</li><li> Lokale und internationale Pressearbeit\r\nEigeninitiative beim Fundraising und bei der Sponsorensuche\r\n</li><li> Koordination der Transporte und Produktionsabläufe\r\n</li><li> Organisation der Reisen und Unterbringung ausstellender Künstler\r\nVertrauensvolle und koordinierte Zusammenarbeit mit dem Direktor und der Leiterin der Geschäftsstelle des Kunstvereins sowie mit der Grafikerin, dem Website-Programmierer, dem Fotografen, dem Filmkurator sowie allen externen Partnern und Organisationen, mit denen der Kunstverein München zusammenarbeitet\r\n \r\nDie Tätigkeit des Koordinators (m/w) ist eine Vollzeitstelle. Die reguläre Arbeitszeit ist von Montag bis Freitag von 10.00 bis 18.00 Uhr. Während der Ausstellungsvorbereitung und des -aufbaus, bei Vermietungen, Eröffnungen und Events wird die Bereitschaft zu flexiblen Arbeitszeiten – einschließlich der Abendstunden – vorausgesetzt.\r\n \r\nAnforderungsprofil:\r\n\r\n</li><li> Deutsch als Muttersprache, fließende                     Englischkenntnisse\r\n</li><li> Herausragende kommunikative Fähigkeiten in Wort und Schrift\r\n</li><li> Sehr gute organisatorische Fähigkeiten\r\nZuverlässigkeit und erfolgreiches Zeitmanagement\r\n</li><li> Intensives Interesse an zeitgenössischer Kunst und die Bereitschaft, sich mit aktuellen künstlerischen Positionen auseinanderzusetzen\r\n</li><li> Erfahrung im Umgang mit der deutschen und internationalen Presse\r\n</li><li> Kenntnisse im Fundraising sowie der erfolgreichen \r\n</li><li> Kontaktaufnahme zu Sponsoren; Erfahrung im Verfassen von Anträgen, Projektbeschreibungen und Evaluationen\r\n</li><li> Flexibilität und Belastbarkeit\r\n \r\nWir bieten:\r\n\r\n</li><li>Die Mitarbeit an ambitionierten Projekten in einem  kleinen, jungen und kreativen Team\r\n</li><li>Eine eigenverantwortliche Tätigkeit mit der Möglichkeit zur Eigeninitiative\r\n</li><li>Enge Kontakte zu Künstlern und der internationalen Kunstwelt\r\n</li><li>Die Möglichkeit, zur positiven Außendarstellung des Kunstvereins beizutragen und seine Wahrnehmung auf lokaler wie internationaler Ebene zu intensivieren\r\n</li><li>Einen der schönsten Arbeitsplätze Münchens direkt am Hofgarten\r\n \r\nBewerbungsdetails:\r\n \r\nPosition:\r\nKoordinator (m/w): Fundraising, Pressearbeit und kuratorische Assistenz\r\n \r\nBewerbungsfrist:\r\n15. November 2015\r\n \r\nBewerbungsgespräche:\r\n9. und 10. Dezember 2015\r\n \r\nAntrittsdatum:\r\n2. Februar 2016\r\n \r\nBitte senden Sie Ihren CV und einen einseitigen Motivationsbrief (vorzugsweise auf Englisch) bis zum 15. November 2015 mit dem Betreff „Koordinator“ an die Adresse: Koordinator@kunstverein-muenchen.de',''),(1381,1,'2015-10-30 16:13:46','2015-11-02 10:29:20',3,'Jobs',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'jobs',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','<u>Coordinator (m/f): Fundraising, Press and Curatorial Assistant</u>\r\n \r\nKunstverein München was founded in 1823 and presents an ambitious program of contemporary art exhibitions, events, publications, and screenings. In 2016, the Kunstverein will expand its activities with a new cinema and bookshop, and is looking for a new Coordinator (m/f) to work with the team in support of the artistic programs.\r\n \r\nThe primary responsibilities of the Coordinator (m/f) will include:\r\n\r\n</li><li> Communication with the local and international press\r\n</li><li> Seeking fundraising and sponsorship opportunities\r\n</li><li> Coordinating shipping and fabrication\r\n</li><li> Coordinating travel and accommodation   for exhibiting artists\r\n</li><li> Collaborating with the director, the                     accounts manager, the graphic designer, website programmer, documentation photographer, the film curator, and other external contractors and    organizations\r\n\r\nThe Coordinator (m/f) is a full-time position. The regular work schedule is 10am until 6pm, Monday through Friday though, in preparation of exhibitions, rentals, opening receptions and events, flexible working days - including the working hours - and evenings are required.\r\n\r\nRequirements:\r\n</li><li> German as a native language, fluency in English\r\n</li><li> Excellent written and verbal communication skills\r\n</li><li> Highly organized\r\n</li><li> Reliable and timely\r\n</li><li> Stong interest in contemporary art \r\n</li><li> Experience communicating with the German and international press\r\n</li><li> Proven ability to source fundraising and sponsorship opportunities, and write applications and project reports and evaluations\r\n</li><li> Flexibility and able to work under pressure \r\n \r\nWhat we offer:\r\n</li><li> Work within a small, young, and creative team\r\n</li><li> Work autonomously with freedom to self-initiate\r\n</li><li> Gain considerable contact with artists and the international art system\r\n</li><li> Contribute significantly to the Kunstverein’s image and further its local and international recognition\r\n</li><li> Work at one of the most beautiful places in Munich \r\n \r\nApplication details: \r\n \r\nPosition:\r\nCoordinator (m/f): Fundraising, Press and Curatorial Assistant \r\n\r\nApplications Due:\r\n15 November 2015\r\n \r\nInterviews with selected candidates:\r\n9 / 10 December 2015 \r\n \r\nStart Date:\r\n2 February 2016\r\n \r\nPlease send your cv and a one-page motivation letter, preferably in English, before 15 November 2015, to Koordinator@kunstverein-muenchen.de with the subject ‘Coordinator’.',''),(1382,1,'2015-09-17 20:40:50','2015-10-30 20:31:20',NULL,'.Dexter Sinister-2',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'dexter-sinister-2',NULL,'2015-10-02 00:00:00','2015-11-22 00:00:00',NULL,NULL,'','Dexter Sinister\r\n<u>On a Universal Serial Bus.*</u>\r\n2 October to 22 November 2015\r\n\r\nDexter Sinister is the compound name of Stuart Bailey and David Reinfurt. Dexter Sinister work at the intersection of graphic design, publishing, and art. <u>On a Universal Serial Bus.*</u> is a survey exhibition at Kunstverein München that follows from three previous projects this year in New York, Athens, and Bregenz. Their titles combine to form a single looping sentence: I’ll be your interface Broadcasting from the Aether At 1:1 Scale On a Universal Serial Bus.* \r\n\r\n<u>On a Universal Serial Bus.*</u> is based on a simultaneous publication of Dexter Sinister’s audio/visual works released in the form of a Universal Serial Bus (USB) memory stick. This drive offers a collection of digital files, while the exhibition presents those same files as a series of objects and installations, along with some related material via the Kunstverein’s regular mediation and promotional channels. Each of the four rooms in the exhibition is based on one of the four projects on the USB stick.\r\n\r\nA speaking asterisk (*) will greet visitors at the entry staircase in place of the usual introductory wall text. Dexter Sinister have programmed this glyph to speak the memory stick’s explanatory readme.txt file in the synthesized voice of curator Isla Leaver-Yap.\r\n\r\nUpstairs, the Kopfsaal will house a three-screen video installation called <u>Identity</u>. This 20-minute projection offers a critical look at the branding strategies of museums, using case studies of Tate, MoMA, and Centre Pompidou, narrated by a voiceover collaged from existing texts. \r\n\r\nThe Treppensaal will accommodate True Mirror, Dexter Sinister’s sprawling project for the 2008 <u>Whitney Biennial</u>. Originally staged as a three-week parallel press office operated from a secret office hidden in the walls of the exhibition, this project extended into multiple formats, including a ‘documents opera’ staged in New York and London, where the original material was performed by its protagonists. The space includes an edited video of this event, a Double-AA side record containing two of the project’s constituent ‘press releases’, a condensed microfiche archive of the initial project, a 16-mm flicker film of the same, and a mirror that offers visitors a view of themselves as others see them.\r\n\r\nThe Grossersaal will host <u>The Last ShOt Clock</u>, a project originally commissioned for <u>Oo/oO</u>, the joint Lithuanian/Cypriot Pavillion at the 2013 <u>Venice Biennial</u>. The space is dominated by two electronic LED scoreboards that keep eccentric time (or score) in their own binary code, plus a musical theme that was part of an hour-long ‘incantation’ delivered live by Dexter Sinister in Vilnius on summer solstice, 2014. Also in the space are a reprogrammed Casio watch that scrolls time digital line segment by digital line segment, an advert for the same, a poster made from light that advertises any and all summer solstices, a photograph of the original Venice clocks in situ, and the tiny microchips that ran them.\r\n\r\nThe Kleinersaal will contain the final piece on the Bus, called <u>Letter & Spirit</u>. This concise animated video tracks the history of the rationalization of typefaces, and adds temporality to typography via a shapeshifting typeface <u>Meta-the-difference-between-the-two-font-4-D</u>. Nearby on the walls are a print of an emblematic glyph, and a poster that announces this particular screening of the work.\r\n\r\nFinally a publication, number 3 in the Kunstverein’s <u>Companion</u> series, will be available at the opening on 2 October 2015. It provides supplementary material written and formatted from within the middle of the production of each piece: the script for <u>Identity</u>, a poem that initiated <u>True Mirror</u>, the complete ‘incantation’ from <u>The Last ShOt Clock</u>, and the full-length essay version of <u>Letter & Spirit</u>. ',''),(1383,1,'2015-02-24 20:04:27','2015-02-24 20:14:50',20,'Cathy Wilkes',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'cathy-wilkes',NULL,'2011-04-16 00:00:00','2011-06-26 00:00:00',NULL,NULL,'','With this exhibition Kunstverein München presents the first comprehensive show outside the UK of British artist and Turner Prize nominee Cathy Wilkes (*1966 in Belfast).\r\n\r\nThe exhibition can be seen as a personal account in which the artist looks back on her oeuvre while adding two newly commissioned works to the selection. The sculptures of Cathy Wilkes are known to have an unusual fragility, by means of the appropriated artefacts and materials she incorporates within them, such as the breakfast plates of porridge she saves of her family. These elements are more comparable to personal sketches that are both anecdotal details and historic.\r\n\r\nThe solo show of Cathy Wilkes at Kunstverein München e.V. will feature new works that are produced in collaboration with GAK Gesellschaft für Aktuelle in Bremen. The exhibition will be on show in Bremen from November this year.\r\n\r\nIt is not often these days that one encounters an artist who allows a level of sentimentality in their work. As it happens, pathos does not fit an image of the artist as an all-knowing aesthetic strategist – an identity that still enjoys the general approval of today’s critical evaluation. It is therefore remarkable that Glasgow-based artist Cathy Wilkes (*1966, Belfast) has never shied away from bringing her emotions to the fore. She is not an artist who tells us how things work. Instead, she exposes vulnerability in being a creative individual. A conversation between Bart van der Heide and Cathy Wilkes.\r\n\r\n<b>Bart van der Heide</b>: Cathy, please allow me to go straight to the burning question: what are your views on pathos in relation to your work?\r\n\r\n<b>Cathy Wilkes</b>: I know that it’s impossible to be objective – I have concluded that over time. And being nonobjective brings all the mysteries of my mind into my work. I think these parts are very important to any artwork: not knowing why something is exactly as it is or why it’s there at all. I want to show these mysteries in an expanded way, but I am not interested in being confessional. I don’t want to share my story or something. I can see and feel that my work shows loss and sadness and I know that my work is brought about by these experiences to an extent. Awareness and openness bring suffering; the possibility of awareness – of enlightenment – is like an everpresent ghost; like a happy land; something which will never be or will never be found.\r\n\r\n‘AS A COLLECTION OF CONSIDERATIONS ARE NOT SEARCHED OUT, SOMETHING COMES FORWARD SLOWLY IN A DIFFERENT WAY. ATTENTION, THIS KIND OF WAITING, HAS A SOFTNESS, A REGISTER OF INCOMPLETENESS LIKE A BABY CLINGING TO HER MOTHER, WHICH SEEMS TO SOFTEN EVERYTHING WHICH IS IN RELATION TO IT. ’ \r\nCATHY WILKES, 2009',''),(1384,1,'2015-11-02 11:10:38','2015-11-26 15:52:04',NULL,'2015-11-05 GespÃ¤ch und Workshop mit Stuart Bertolotti-Bailey',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2015-11-05-gespch-und-workshop-mit-stuart-bertolotti-bailey',NULL,'2015-11-05 19:00:00','2015-11-06 19:00:00',NULL,NULL,'','Gespäch und Workshop mit Stuart Bertolotti-Bailey, eingeladen von der Klasse Nikolai\r\n\r\nGespräch mit Stuart Bertolotti-Bailey im Klassenzimmer von Nikolai AEG_19\r\nDonnerstag, 5. November 2015, 19 Uh\r\n\r\nWorkshop und Führung durch die Ausstellung im Kunstverein München\r\nFreitag, 6. November 2015, 11 Uhr',''),(1385,1,'2015-11-02 12:12:07','2015-11-25 10:46:34',NULL,